    <h1>Abstraction in Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)</h1>

    <p>
        Imagine a <strong>TV remote</strong> 🎮.
        You press a button to change the channel or adjust the volume, but you don’t need to know how the circuits inside the remote work.
        This is <strong>Abstraction</strong> — hiding the <em>complex details</em> and showing only the <em>essential features</em> you need.
    </p>

    <p>
        In programming, <strong>abstraction</strong> means focusing on <em>what an object does</em> instead of <em>how it does it</em>.
        It helps simplify complex systems so you can use them without worrying about the internal logic.
    </p>

    <h2>How Abstraction Works</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>
            In C#, we achieve abstraction mainly using:
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Abstract Classes</strong> – a blueprint with some rules (methods) that other classes must follow.</li>
                <li><strong>Interfaces</strong> – a complete contract that classes agree to implement.</li>
            </ul>
        </li>
        <li>You cannot create an object directly from an abstract class or interface.</li>
        <li>Other classes (called <strong>derived classes</strong>) provide the actual details and behavior.</li>
        <li>This way, the user only sees the “buttons” (methods) and not the hidden implementation.</li>
    </ul>

