    <h2>Real-World Examples of Abstraction</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Car driving 🚗</strong>: You use the steering wheel and pedals, but don’t worry about how the engine works inside.</li>
        <li><strong>ATM machine 🏦</strong>: You press buttons to withdraw cash, without knowing the banking software or money-counting mechanism inside.</li>
        <li><strong>Smartphone 📱</strong>: You tap an app icon, and it opens, without needing to understand how the operating system launches it.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Why Abstraction is Important</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Reduces complexity</strong> – makes large programs easier to understand.</li>
        <li><strong>Improves reusability</strong> – different classes can use the same abstract idea in their own way.</li>
        <li><strong>Supports flexibility</strong> – code is easier to extend and maintain when the details are hidden.</li>
        <li><strong>Encourages cleaner design</strong> – forces developers to separate “what” something does from “how” it does it.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Key Points to Remember</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Abstraction is about <strong>hiding details</strong> and showing only what’s important.</li>
        <li>It is implemented using <strong>abstract classes</strong> and <strong>interfaces</strong> in C#.</li>
        <li>You cannot create objects from abstract classes or interfaces directly.</li>
        <li>Other classes must provide the hidden implementation (the “how”).</li>
    </ul>

